            "replies_count": 1,
            "reblogs_count": 0,
            "favourites_count": 0,
            "edited_at": null,
            "content": "<p><span class=\"h-card\" translate=\"no\"><a href=\"https://climatejustice.social/@breadandcircuses\" class=\"u-url mention\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">@<span>breadandcircuses</span></a></span> I may have misunderstood, but my understanding is that the orange line measures the annual amount of CO2 we put in the air while the dotted one measures how much there currently is.</p><p>In which case, it would make sense for the dotted one to keep climbing up as long as the orange one doesn't drop to 0. This doesn't necessarily invalidate the feedback hypothesis, it just seems like most of the growth is likely still coming from human-linker CO2 emissions.</p>",
