        {
            "id": "112883691840548598",
            "created_at": "2024-07-31T23:27:17.000Z",
            "in_reply_to_id": "112881244759828375",
            "in_reply_to_account_id": "109298515581226227",
            "sensitive": false,
            "spoiler_text": "",
            "visibility": "unlisted",
            "language": "en",
            "uri": "https://mastodon.au/users/largess/statuses/112883691495170700",
            "url": "https://mastodon.au/@largess/112883691495170700",
            "replies_count": 0,
            "reblogs_count": 3,
            "favourites_count": 0,
            "edited_at": null,
            "content": "<p><span class=\"h-card\" translate=\"no\"><a href=\"https://climatejustice.social/@breadandcircuses\" class=\"u-url mention\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">@<span>breadandcircuses</span></a></span><br>&gt;Emissions of carbon dioxide (CO\u2082) appear to have peaked during the last several years in the United States and in most countries in Europe. That's good, right?</p><p>---</p><p>Remembering lots of emissions aren't even counted eg shipping, international flights, military. So saying they've peaked is misguided if you aren't even counting them all.</p><p>That aside, as you pointed  out even  emissions flat lining is failure, they need to be going down at about 10%-15% per annum but ignoring that,  mostly becase the flat lining emissions comes from outsourcing them and the duplicitous way we count emissions in the first place.  </p><p>If you count consumptive emissions theres no chance US emissions have decreased becase there's been no behavioural change  eg no closing of airports and banning flying, no banning cars and meat eating pets, no banning cruise ships, private jets etc, no 1/2ing of the military etc, that is no doing the things that need doing to reduce emsisons.</p><p>Professor Deiter Helm discusses  this sleight of hand in this article from years ago</p><p><a href=\"https://e360.yale.edu/features/forget_kyoto_putting_a_tax_on_carbon_consumption\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\" translate=\"no\" target=\"_blank\"><span class=\"invisible\">https://</span><span class=\"ellipsis\">e360.yale.edu/features/forget_</span><span class=\"invisible\">kyoto_putting_a_tax_on_carbon_consumption</span></a></p><p>---</p><p>&gt;it's imperative that fossil fuel extraction and consumption are drastically reduced, beginning immediately.</p><p>----</p><p>It's the drug dealer problem, banning oil extraction in the US and you'll buy it from Russia etc. The only solution is demand destruction; banning Cars, banning flying, banning cruise ships, private jets, jet skis, etal we've never been serious about anything but climate theatre :(</p>",
